1. Cables and connectors
    - Guided media 
        -   Co-axial Cable
        -   Twisted Pair Cable
            -   Shielded
            -   UNShielded
        -   Fiber optic
    - Unguided media
        -   Wireless medium

2. Physical Topologies
    - Mesh Topology
        - Cables : n*(n-1)/2
        - Ports : n-1 ports for every device
        - Cost : High
        - Reliability : Most
        - Security : Most
    - Star Topology
        - Cables : n
        - Ports : 1 ports for every device
        - Cost : Low
        - Reliability : Poor
        - Security : Less
    - Bus Topology
        - Cables : n+1
        - Ports : 1 ports for every device
        - Cost : Low
        - Reliability : Poor
        - Security : Less (Due to broadcasting backbone)
    - Ring Topology
        - Cables : n
        - Ports : 1 ports for every device
        - Cost : Low
        - Reliability : Poor
        - Security : Less (Due to broadcasting backbone)

3. Network Devices
    - Repeater : 
        . Use : Regains the original energy any attenuated data.
        . Ports : 2
        . Access layer : Physical Layer
    - Hub :
        . Use : A Repeater with multiple pair of ports
        . Ports : 2n
        . Access layer : Physical Layer
    - Bridge :
        . Use : Connects two (same or different) topological systems.
        . Ports : 2
        . Access layer : Physical Layer & Data link layer
        , Types :
            - Static (Manual entry needed in the MAC address - Port number lookup table)
            - Dynamic (Maintains Self trained MAC address - Port number lookup table)
    - Switch :
        . Use : Establishes connection in multiple topological systems
        . Ports : 2n
        . Access Layer : Physical Layer & Data link layer
    - Router :
        . Use : Establishes connection between multiple network devices (world wide web)
        . Port : Software based logically designed
        . Access layer : Physical, Data link & Network Layer

4. Transmission Mode :
    - Simplex -> One way data travel connection for all time
    - Half-Duplex -> One way data travel at a single moment
    - Full-Dulex -> dual way data travel at any moment

5. Multiplexing :
    Logically programming existing number network channels for efficient and multiple usage.

6. Encoding :
    - Digital-to-Analog
    - Analog-to-Digital
    - Digital-to-Digital

